				 Ally rift widens in Karnataka
 OUR BUREAU AND AGENCIES																								Oct. 1: BJP ministers in Karnataka handed resignation letters to party colleague and deputy chief minister B.S. Yediyurappa as coalition partner Janata Dal (Secular) showed little inclination to transfer power even two days before the scheduled changeover.																								Our resignation letters are with Yediyurappa. If (chief minister H.D.) Kumaraswamy does not step down by tomorrow, all the resignation letters would be handed over to him in the evening, a BJP minister said.																								There is no further scope for negotiations, said central emissary Yashwant Sinha.																								The JD (S) postponed a meeting of its legislature party. It said its MLAs, leaders and executive members would meet in Bangalore on October 4 and the political affairs committee in Delhi on October 5.																								I have to consult my partymen before deciding the issue, Kumaraswamy told a delegation headed by Yediyurappa.
